Model Selection: Gila Monster Detection

Sienna Solis-Stokes

Introduction

For this exercise I decided to use my thesis data to create models which best describe Gila monster detection along a transect. I calculated the mean temperature, the median rockiness index (same index from previous assignment), the median elevation, shrub density, and total adult prey species observed (prey presence) along a transect. The data consists of 504 transects across 6 sites.

Model Selection

Next I created 7 models with corresponding biological hypotheses.

model_01 <- glm(detection ~ rockiness + elevation, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)
model_02 <- glm(detection ~ rockiness + air_temp, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)
model_03 <- glm(detection ~ rockiness + shrub_density, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)
model_04 <- glm(detection ~ rockiness + prey_presence, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)
model_05 <- glm(detection ~ rockiness + shrub_density + prey_presence, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)
model_06 <- glm(detection ~ shrub_density + prey_presence, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)
model_07 <- glm(detection ~ rockiness + elevation + air_temp, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)

Model 1 (rockiness + elevation): Detection probability increases on sandier, lower-elevation transects where thermal conditions and sandier substrates promote above-ground activity and sign visibility.

Model 2 (rockiness + air temp): Detection probability rises on sandier transects and during warmer air temperatures, consistent with greater surface activity and clearer track/visual detectability.

Model 3 (rockiness + shrub density): Detection probability increases on sandier, sparsely vegetated transects (higher visibility/surface activity) and declines on rockier, shrub-dense transects.

Model 4 (rockiness + prey presence): Detection probability increases on sandier transects and where prey are present (nest predators), and foraging activity is easier to detect on loose substrates.

Model 5 (rockiness + shrub density + prey presence): Detection probability is higher on sandier transects when prey are present, but dense shrubs reduce detectability and potential prey-vegetation associations may lead to more foraging activity which could offset reduced detectability.

Model 6 (shrub density + prey presence): Detection probability increases with prey presence and decreases with shrub density due to visual obstruction and more compact substrates.

Model 7 (rockiness + elevation + air temp): Detection probability increases with sandier substrates and warmer temperatures; elevation has an added effect.

  • Detection probability increases with air temperature; biologically this (mostly) makes sense as Gilas are ectotherms and have greater surface activity at warmer temperatures; HOWEVER they to have a low tolerance for high temperatures so this relationship is not continuous in reality.

  • Detection probability increases as the rockiness index increases; in this case the results suggest that detections are more likely on sandier transects

  • Elevation has little influence on detection after accounting for the substrate texture and air temperture.

  • The conditional average is nearly identical to the full average, so variable inclusion is consistent across top models.

  • Intercept: high p-value most likely because of the low amount of detections.

Thus the supported hypothesis is that Gila monster detection probability increases with warmer air temperatures and sandier substrates with elevation playing a minor role.

Mixed-effects Models

I wanted to see how (and if) my results would change with mixed-effects models, so I created 7 more identical models that account for the random effect of each transect nested within each site.

gm_df <- gm_df %>%
  mutate(site_id = factor(site_id),
         transect_id = factor(transect_id))

model_08 <- glmer(detection ~ rockiness + elevation + (1|site_id/transect_id), family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)
model_09 <- glmer(detection ~ rockiness + air_temp + (1|site_id/transect_id), family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)
model_10 <- glmer(detection ~ rockiness + shrub_density + (1|site_id/transect_id), family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)
model_11 <- glmer(detection ~ rockiness + prey_presence + (1|site_id/transect_id), family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)
model_12 <- glmer(detection ~ rockiness + shrub_density + prey_presence  + (1|site_id/transect_id), family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)
model_13 <- glmer(detection ~ shrub_density + prey_presence + (1|site_id/transect_id), family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)
model_14 <- glmer(detection ~ rockiness + elevation + air_temp + (1|site_id/transect_id), family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = gm_df)

Then I looked at the summary tables to compare all 14 models.

When adding in the mixed-effects models, our model comparison results completely change. By taking in to account the random effects of site and transect, the only supported model is model 13 which uses shrub density and prey presence as the predictor variables.

  • After accounting for site/transect, detection is higher on transects with greater shrub density and slightly lower where prey counts are higher.

  • Adding other predictors (rockiness, elevation, shrub density) increased AICc without improving fit — meaning they didn’t add useful information.

  • The random intercepts (1 | site_id/transect_id) improved the model compared with non-mixed GLMs, capturing spatial structure among transects.

  • These results go against all my apriori hypotheses that a higher shrub density would decrease detectability.

Then I wanted to use the performance package to check the highest ranked GLM model and the highest ranked mixed-effects model.
